[{"sha":"b359894a62f2c09170389f9c742fbf4b4f4719e0","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@google.com"},"message":"Support all datatypes for Xtensa softmax implementation.

 * This allows the micro_speech and person_detect examples to be usable
   with the optimized xtensa kernels.

 * enabled all the softmax kernel test cases for Xtensa (since we have a
   fallback to the reference kernels).

 * The keyword_benchmark specific variant is moved to its own .cc file
   since that allows the Xtensa linker to properly drop unsused symbols
   and ensures that the binary size for the keyword_benchmark is
   unchanged.

Manually tested that the following tests pass:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_person_detection_test_int8 -j8
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_micro_speech_test -j8
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_kernel_softmax_test -j8
```

Confirmed that the binary size for the keyword_benchmark is unchanged (relative to tip of tree):
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade keyword_benchmark -j8 BUILD_TYPE=release
xt-size tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/xtensa_fusion_f1_release/bin/keyword_benchmark
```

Gives:
```
   text	   data	    bss	    dec	    hex	filename
  70368	  41140	  24856	 136364	  214ac	tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/xtensa_fusion_f1_release/bin/keyword_benchmark

        signal_linux_test.go:32: assertion failed: continued (string) != hangup (string)

Add schedule hints EARLY_AS_POSSIBLE and LATE_AS_POSSIBLE to custom-calls.
This supports a custom-call case, where a logical operation can be lowered into
two HLOs (e.g., PerformX and PerformXDone). We can utilize this mechanism to
either hide host latencies between the pair of the custom-calls or the two calls
can more accurately identify the def-use relationship (typically PerformX is

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MRS-OS/moby/commits/7daf2db62a69cb6b341addf94d5da82759d7b6c2"},{"sha":"26eddc16a887e84f31ef540e0568cbb998dfe155","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"systemd: add "Delegate=yes" to docker's service file

We need to add delegate yes to docker's service file so that it can
manage the cgroups of the processes that it launches without systemd
interfering with them and moving the processes after it is reloaded.

       Delegate=
           Turns on delegation of further resource control partitioning to
           processes of the unit. For unprivileged services (i.e. those
           using the User= setting), this allows processes to create a
           subhierarchy beneath its control group path. For privileged
           services and scopes, this ensures the processes will have all
           control group controllers enabled.

This is the proper fix for issue moby/moby#20152

[{"sha":"711788abab53ab00bb927044b0b6a6550a22b117","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Adds a variation of decompose-resource-ops pass to operate only within device cluster and reachable functions.

Decomposing resource ops in the entire module is not always desirable. For example, MLIR TF-XLA bridge would have device clusters and also ops to be run on host. Decomposing all ops can lead to performance regressions as well as introduce ops that do not have kernels on host. Thus, a module pass variation that only operates within device cluster and reachable functions is required.

   with the optimized xtensa kernels.

   fallback to the reference kernels).

 * The keyword_benchmark specific variant is moved to its own .cc file
   since that allows the Xtensa linker to properly drop unsused symbols
   and ensures that the binary size for the keyword_benchmark is
   unchanged.

Manually tested that the following tests pass:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_person_detection_test_int8 -j8

```

Confirmed that the binary size for the keyword_benchmark is unchanged (relative to tip of tree):
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade keyword_benchmark -j8 BUILD_TYPE=release
xt-size tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/xtensa_fusion_f1_release/bin/keyword_benchmark
```

Gives:
```

Change-Id: I55e4b514c8e96867565bf880d82e03098b52beb6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/54e7ef979e9b61d624e33fee2855bd3c56c52869"},{"sha":"711788abab53ab00bb927044b0b6a6550a22b117","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Adds a variation of decompose-resource-ops pass to operate only within device cluster and reachable functions.

Decomposing resource ops in the entire module is not always desirable. For example, MLIR TF-XLA bridge would have device clusters and also ops to be run on host.    unchanged.

```

```

Confirmed that the binary size for the keyword_benchmark is unchanged (relative to tip of tree):
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade keyword_benchmark -j8 BUILD_TYPE=release
xt-size tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/xtensa_fusion_f1_release/bin/keyword_benchmark
```

    determine the actual operation being executed at that time.

either hide host latencies between the pair of the custom-calls or the two calls

[{"sha":"7de009c346cd7c67b51fce3c87e855e4f5e3d1be","author":{"name":"Trent Lo","email":"7ddb1753734378bc8a5ee2f8f682002ac2d0087e@nvidia.com"},"message":"[XLA/GPU] Add CustomCallSchedule to give schedule hints to custom-calls.

Add schedule hints EARLY_AS_POSSIBLE and LATE_AS_POSSIBLE to custom-calls.
This supports a custom-call case, where a logical operation can be lowered into
two HLOs (e.g., PerformX and PerformXDone). We can utilize this mechanism to
either hide host latencies between the pair of the custom-calls or the two calls
can more accurately identify the def-use relationship (typically PerformX is
scheduled right after all of its producers have been scheduled and PerformXDone

[{"sha":"b359894a62f2c09170389f9c742fbf4b4f4719e0","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@google.com"},"message":"Support all datatypes for Xtensa softmax implementation.

 * This allows the micro_speech and person_detect examples to be usable
   with the optimized xtensa kernels.

 * enabled all the softmax kernel test cases for Xtensa (since we have a
   fallback to the reference kernels).

 * The keyword_benchmark specific variant is moved to its own .cc file
   since that allows the Xtensa linker to properly drop unsused symbols
   and ensures that the binary size for the keyword_benchmark is
   unchanged.

Manually tested that the following tests pass:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_person_detection_test_int8 -j8
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_micro_speech_test -j8
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_kernel_softmax_test -j8
```

Confirmed that the binary size for the keyword_benchmark is unchanged (relative to tip of tree):
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade keyword_benchmark -j8 BUILD_TYPE=release
xt-size tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/xtensa_fusion_f1_release/bin/keyword_benchmark
```

Gives:
```
   text	   data	    bss	    dec	    hex	filename

[{"sha":"b359894a62f2c09170389f9c742fbf4b4f4719e0","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@google.com"},"message":"Support all datatypes for Xtensa softmax implementation.

 * This allows the micro_speech and person_detect examples to be usable
   with the optimized xtensa kernels.

 * enabled all the softmax kernel test cases for Xtensa (since we have a
   fallback to the reference kernels).

 * The keyword_benchmark specific variant is moved to its own .cc file
   since that allows the Xtensa linker to properly drop unsused symbols
   and ensures that the binary size for the keyword_benchmark is
   unchanged.

Manually tested that the following tests pass:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_person_detection_test_int8 -j8
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_micro_speech_test -j8
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test_kernel_softmax_test -j8
```

Confirmed that the binary size for the keyword_benchmark is unchanged (relative to tip of tree):
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade keyword_benchmark -j8 BUILD_TYPE=release
xt-size tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/xtensa_fusion_f1_release/bin/keyword_benchmark
```

Gives:
```
   text	   data	    bss	    dec	    hex	filename
  70368	  41140	  24856	 136364	  214ac	tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/xtensa_fusion_f1_release/bin/keyword_benchmark

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vdavalon01/moby/commits/7daf2db62a69cb6b341addf94d5da82759d7b6c2"},{"sha":"26eddc16a887e84f31ef540e0568cbb998dfe155","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"systemd: add "Delegate=yes" to docker's service file

We need to add delegate yes to docker's service file so that it can
manage the cgroups of the processes that it launches without systemd
interfering with them and moving the processes after it is reloaded.

       Delegate=
           Turns on delegation of further resource control partitioning to
           processes of the unit. For unprivileged services (i.e. those
           using the User= setting), this allows processes to create a
           subhierarchy beneath its control group path. For privileged
           services and scopes, this ensures the processes will have all
           control group controllers enabled.

This is the proper fix for issue moby/moby#20152

PiperOrigin-RevId: 371711365
Change-Id: Ifeba854a51e43d22949ab8a2f83429668e20821a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/irvineoy/tensorflow/commits/54fa3510e5a409ecb8a7be675fe444442badbec6"},{"sha":"90ed61e99f5768854f252bfc669d4160e38b84b8","author":{"name":"Jiri Simsa","email":"b53bfee97ac78a1d2afd0ef6138945f352c1fa9d@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data] Refactoring of dataset finalization.

This CL introduces a new utility method `FinalizeDataset`, which is intended to be applied to `DatasetBase` representing the final transformation of a user-defined input pipeline before creating an iterator for it. The method ends up performing static graph optimizations and appends a new `Root` transformation that combines the functionality of existing internal transformations -- `ModelDataset`, `MaxIntraOpParallelismDataset`, and `PrivateThreadpoolDataset`.

This CL also performs refactoring of `FinalizeDatasetOp` and `OptimizeDatasetOp` to avoid duplication of logic and switches the `tf.data.experimental.save()` and `tf.data.experimental.TFRecordWriter()` APIs to use the new finalization mechanism, replacing the previous mechanism based on `_apply_options()` and `FinalizeDatasetOp`.

Subsequent changes will make a similar switch for other mechanisms that iterate through a tf.data dataset, such as `tf.data.Iterator` or `tf.data.Dataset.reduce()`.

Add schedule hints EARLY_AS_POSSIBLE and LATE_AS_POSSIBLE to custom-calls.
This supports a custom-call case, where a logical operation can be lowered into
two HLOs (e.g., PerformX and PerformXDone). We can utilize this mechanism to
either hide host latencies between the pair of the custom-calls or the two calls
can more accurately identify the def-use relationship (typically PerformX is
scheduled right after all of its producers have been scheduled and PerformXDone
is scheduled right before its first consumer.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ashutosh1919/tensorflow/commits/7de009c346cd7c67b51fce3c87e855e4f5e3d1be"},{"sha":"f2227bac3ba93d049322c8d55123918c282145ee","author":{"name":"Trent Lo","email":"7ddb1753734378bc8a5ee2f8f682002ac2d0087e@nvidia.com"},"message":"[XLA/GPU] Make postprocessor_to_custom_schedule respect control dependencies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ashutosh1919/tensorflow/commits/f2227bac3ba93d049322c8d55123918c282145ee"},{"sha":"8ac6a195ca190fd45b9df42253472a0760adc622","author":{"name":"Trent Lo","email":"7ddb1753734378bc8a5ee2f8f682002ac2d0087e@nvidia.com"},"message":"[XLA/GPU] Test CustomCallSchedule::EARLY_AS_POSSIBLE in hlo_parser_test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ashutosh1919/tensorflow/commits/8ac6a195ca190fd45b9df42253472a0760adc622"},{"sha":"ba453144301af295b09643ab3f3fde5d8055756d","author":{"name":"Trent Lo","email":"7ddb1753734378bc8a5ee2f8f682002ac2d0087e@nvidia.com"},"message":"[XLA] Initialize custom_call_schedule_ in HloCustomCallInstruction.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ashutosh1919/tensorflow/commits/ba453144301af295b09643ab3f3fde5d8055756d"},{"sha":"d9e163da42f9538e9c03984f8773094b75a2f151","author":{"name":"Trent Lo","email":"7ddb1753734378bc8a5ee2f8f682002ac2d0087e@nvidia.com"},"message":"[XLA/GPU] Rename enums in CustomCallSchedule

[{"sha":"7de009c346cd7c67b51fce3c87e855e4f5e3d1be","author":{"name":"Trent Lo","email":"7ddb1753734378bc8a5ee2f8f682002ac2d0087e@nvidia.com"},"message":"[XLA/GPU] Add CustomCallSchedule to give schedule hints to custom-calls.

Add schedule hints EARLY_AS_POSSIBLE and LATE_AS_POSSIBLE to custom-calls.
This supports a custom-call case, where a logical operation can be lowered into
two HLOs (e.g., PerformX and PerformXDone). We can utilize this mechanism to
either hide host latencies between the pair of the custom-calls or the two calls
can more accurately identify the def-use relationship (typically PerformX is
scheduled right after all of its producers have been scheduled and PerformXDone
is scheduled right before its first consumer.)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/7de009c346cd7c67b51fce3c87e855e4f5e3d1be"},{"sha":"f2227bac3ba93d049322c8d55123918c282145ee","author":{"name":"Trent Lo","email":"7ddb1753734378bc8a5ee2f8f682002ac2d0087e@nvidia.com"},"message":"[XLA/GPU] Make postprocessor_to_custom_schedule respect control dependencies.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/f2227bac3ba93d049322c8d55123918c282145ee"},{"sha":"8ac6a195ca190fd45b9df42253472a0760adc622","author":{"name":"Trent Lo","email":"7ddb1753734378bc8a5ee2f8f682002ac2d0087e@nvidia.com"},"message":"[XLA/GPU] Test CustomCallSchedule::EARLY_AS_POSSIBLE in hlo_parser_test.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/8ac6a195ca190fd45b9df42253472a0760adc622"},{"sha":"ba453144301af295b09643ab3f3fde5d8055756d","author":{"name":"Trent Lo","email":"7ddb1753734378bc8a5ee2f8f682002ac2d0087e@nvidia.com"},"message":"[XLA] Initialize custom_call_schedule_ in HloCustomCallInstruction.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/ba453144301af295b09643ab3f3fde5d8055756d"},{"sha":"d9e163da42f9538e9c03984f8773094b75a2f151","author":{"name":"Trent Lo","email":"7ddb1753734378bc8a5ee2f8f682002ac2d0087e@nvidia.com"},"message":"[XLA/GPU] Rename enums in CustomCallSchedule

workers share the devices, which is desired to reduce the number of GPUs needed
for testing. For NCCL tests however, we need to make different workers using
different GPUs.

This change sets CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES on worker processes if share_gpu is False.

Change-Id: Ic57e6298a70604e5f72b955daf7064fadfbfb3f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/a27bbfd04c7cb03fc4f6b110e3032117bbaa375e"},{"sha":"9f594b848ac12c98518a544198fc1c0571f68ce1","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Support each worker using different GPUs in multi_process_runner

workers share the devices, which is desired to reduce the number of GPUs needed

different GPUs.

This change sets CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES on worker processes if share_gpu is False.

Stitching Detailed Tutorial Improvements

* Add Vertical Wave Correction

The user has the possibility to pass "vert" as wave_correct parameter. However, in the code "cv.detail.WAVE_CORRECT_HORIZ" ist fixed. This change proposes changes so that the wave correction is done vertically if the user passes "vert" as wave_correct parameter. The variable "do_wave_correct" is replaced by None which is passed to the variable "wave_correct" if the user chooses "no" for wave correction.

* Correct fixed conf_thresh

According to the documentation, [cv.detail.leaveBiggestComponent](https://docs.opencv.org/4.5.1/d7/d74/group__stitching__rotation.html#ga855d2fccbcfc3b3477b34d415be5e786) takes features, the pairwise_matches and the conf_threshold as input.
In the tutorial, however, conf_threshold is fixed at 0.3 even though the user can pass conf_thresh as parameter which is 1 by default. two HLOs (e.g., PerformX and PerformXDone). We can utilize this mechanism to

[{"sha":"2fea30f14603613b40d8ce37c8ea7951f87abd1b","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"hack: add script to regenerate certificates

Certificates were originally added in c000cb64712349141596318dea2a8de2462c8f81,
but did not include a script to generate them. Current versions of Go expect
certificates to use SAN instead of Common Name fields, so updating the script
to include those;

    x509: certificate relies on legacy Common Name field, use SANs or temporarily
    enable Common Name matching with GODEBUG=x509ignoreCN=0

Some fields were updated to be a bit more descriptive (instead of "replaceme"),
and the `-text` option was used to include a human-readable variant of the
content.

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

Initial attempt was to just skip the failing subtest (using the `test.disable_with_predicate` decorator), but that causes the following failure in non-ROCm builds

```
raise RuntimeError('You appear to be running a parameterized test case '
RuntimeError: You appear to be running a parameterized test case without having inherited from parameterized.TestCase. This is bad because none of your test cases are actually being run. You may also be using another decorator before the parameterized one, in which case you should reverse the order.
```

Reversing the decorator order results in a different error

```
ValueError: The test does not take parameters that were passed : {'use_adapt'} .
```

so abandoning that approach and adding a `no_rocm` tag to skip the test completely

The subtest being failing on the ROCm platform is `KPLTest.testTrainAndServe`

The error does not seem to be ROCm specific, and am hoping it will be root-caused and fixed in upstream.
Skipping these subtests for now to get the ROCm unit-tests passing again.

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

This is a CUDA specific test, and should not be enabled on the ROCm platform","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/25d3a3e4e033886fdae95f8b4e5f4bb7fb0e75a3"},{"sha":"1fc1d59b7310a135082d50b9b84c1a8e79438f41","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"ROCM specific workaround for an MLIR unittest that results in a call to `ThenBlasGemmWithAlgorithm`

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

```

```

so abandoning that approach and adding a `no_rocm` tag to skip the test completely

clarify the "disconnected/connected" concepts in the sample `page_live_test.exs` that is generated when running `phx new --live`. Why? === The `PageLiveTest` that is generated with the `phx new --live` installer seems to be either incorrect or uses confusing language. The test currently shows the `live/2` helper returning a `disconnected_html` as the third element in the three tuple: ```elixir {:ok, page_live, disconnected_html} = live(conn, "/") ``` The term "disconnected" is confusing because [`LiveViewTest` docs][test docs] use that same term to describe the disconnected HTML returned from the stateless HTTP request. Take the examples from [`LiveViewTest` docs][test docs]: ```elixir test "disconnected and connected mount", %{conn: conn} do conn = get(conn, "/my-path") assert html_response(conn, 200) =~ "

My Disconnected View

" {:ok, view, html} = live(conn) end ``` The disconnected view is the one rendered via the `get/2` + `html_response/2`. By contrast the `html` returned by `live/2` renders the "Connected View": ```elixir test "connected mount", %{conn: conn} do {:ok, _view, html} = live(conn, "/my-path") assert html =~ "

My Connected View

" end ``` From some independent testing (I'd be happy to provide a sample app if that's helpful), the latter seems to be true: the `html` returned by the `live/2` helper is the connected HTML, not the disconnected one. Thus, this commit seeks to clarify that distinction by more closely updating the sample test in the installer to match those show in `Phoenix.LiveViewTest` docs. ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

configuration. This will allow the provider to be referenced by name in

If the user gives an index-less address for a resource that expects
instance keys then previously we would've emitted one error per declared
instance of the resource, which is overwhelming and not especially
helpful.

Instead, we'll deal with that check prior to expanding resources into
resource instances, and thus we can report a single error which talks
about all of the instances at once.

This does unfortunately come at the expense of splitting the logic for
dealing with the "force replace" addresses into two places, which will
likely make later maintenance harder. In an attempt to mitigate that,
I've included a comment in each place that mentions the other place, which
hopefully future maintainers will keep up-to-date if that situation
changes.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/StephanHCB/terraform/commits/c63c06d3c4d09a1bf1a1adc20216503e0cc2f881"},{"sha":"2756f5ed08fdc16e12e93d602ab01f56f3269b9b","author":{"name":"Chris Arcand","email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com"},"message":"Update Terraform Cloud/Enterprise client to v0.14.0","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/StephanHCB/terraform/commits/2756f5ed08fdc16e12e93d602ab01f56f3269b9b"},{"sha":"e9c9092c407c3f1aa5f7b081a907d6c2aaafe0d2","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix missing trailing newline","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/StephanHCB/terraform/commits/e9c9092c407c3f1aa5f7b081a907d6c2aaafe0d2"},{"sha":"3a9b369b43bc2759b3bf5258caf9b31631c8a20a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views/json: Fix diag crash with invalid highlight

Some diagnostic sources (I'm looking at you, HCL) fail to set the end of
the subject range. This is a bug in those code paths, but we can ensure
that we generate valid JSON diagnostics by checking for it here.

useful is displayed.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/StephanHCB/terraform/commits/3a9b369b43bc2759b3bf5258caf9b31631c8a20a"},{"sha":"25f99857cfce37e9e5979e6004052afa54d5d8ed","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Fix crash with invalid JSON diagnostics

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ameyag/moby/commits/7daf2db62a69cb6b341addf94d5da82759d7b6c2"},{"sha":"26eddc16a887e84f31ef540e0568cbb998dfe155","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"systemd: add "Delegate=yes" to docker's service file

We need to add delegate yes to docker's service file so that it can
manage the cgroups of the processes that it launches without systemd
interfering with them and moving the processes after it is reloaded.

       Delegate=
           Turns on delegation of further resource control partitioning to
           processes of the unit. For unprivileged services (i.e. those
           using the User= setting), this allows processes to create a
           subhierarchy beneath its control group path. For privileged
           services and scopes, this ensures the processes will have all
           control group controllers enabled.

This is the proper fix for issue moby/moby#20152

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

Initial attempt was to just skip the failing subtest (using the `test.disable_with_predicate` decorator), but that causes the following failure in non-ROCm builds

```

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

Certificates were originally added in c000cb64712349141596318dea2a8de2462c8f81,
but did not include a script to generate them. Current versions of Go expect
certificates to use SAN instead of Common Name fields, so updating the script
to include those;

    x509: certificate relies on legacy Common Name field, use SANs or temporarily
    enable Common Name matching with GODEBUG=x509ignoreCN=0

Some fields were updated to be a bit more descriptive (instead of "replaceme"),
and the `-text` option was used to include a human-readable variant of the
content.

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

Certificates were originally added in c000cb64712349141596318dea2a8de2462c8f81,
but did not include a script to generate them. Current versions of Go expect
certificates to use SAN instead of Common Name fields, so updating the script
to include those;

    x509: certificate relies on legacy Common Name field, use SANs or temporarily
    enable Common Name matching with GODEBUG=x509ignoreCN=0

Some fields were updated to be a bit more descriptive (instead of "replaceme"),
and the `-text` option was used to include a human-readable variant of the
content.

[{"sha":"506f47ba838453af4e4e7139ef2b3acb4c55ba49","author":{"name":"Jared Duke","email":"ea37426a46b29e75a9167ee55a7a94e3477621b0@google.com"},"message":"[tf.lite] Add GPU manifest for targeting Android 12 ("S")

Targeting Android 12 requires explicit declaration of any referenced
native vendor libraries. Include the necessary tags in a GPU-specific
manifest, such that downstream apps inherit them when adding the GPU
library as a dependency, enabling use of vendor-provided OpenCL libraries.

Note that for apps not targeting Android 12 ("S") explicitly, there
should be no change in behavior (with or without this CL).

Also note that this manifest cannot be used by default for OSS builds,
as it requires AGP 4.2.0; this will be addressed in follow-up work.

Causing the test to fail:

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/moby/commits/2842639e0e22bc2f91271603fb9990fa2ac8ad2e"},{"sha":"2fea30f14603613b40d8ce37c8ea7951f87abd1b","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"hack: add script to regenerate certificates

Certificates were originally added in c000cb64712349141596318dea2a8de2462c8f81,
but did not include a script to generate them. Current versions of Go expect
certificates to use SAN instead of Common Name fields, so updating the script
to include those;

    x509: certificate relies on legacy Common Name field, use SANs or temporarily
    enable Common Name matching with GODEBUG=x509ignoreCN=0

Some fields were updated to be a bit more descriptive (instead of "replaceme"),
and the `-text` option was used to include a human-readable variant of the
content.

Reformats output of GreedyMemoryPlanner:PrintMemoryPlan() to make it
simpler to interpret.

Per-buffer info line improvements:

(a) Reduces text quantity to make it easier to scan for information.
(b) Moves size to near front line, to make it simpler for the eye to
    find this information.
(c) Includes ordinal letter used in per-time display below to make it
    simpler to cross-reference.

Per time improvements:

(a) Includes tick number. This is useful in larger models for cross
    referencing to the per-buffer information and also for helping to
    determine the actual operation being executed at that time.

    identify memory bottlenecks.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/0f32b446cf8cc140f8eaf02c1671e842ad126338"},{"sha":"1af9d9130ca3186125c72c6f72a4fbb60763e056","author":{"name":"Alan Green","email":"97e77871b5fcc4941bebceb4338c97c1fd149f8c@google.com"},"message":"micro: fix unused-variable-warning

[{"sha":"9f594b848ac12c98518a544198fc1c0571f68ce1","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Support each worker using different GPUs in multi_process_runner

NCCL requires different ranks to use different physical devices. By default
workers share the devices, which is desired to reduce the number of GPUs needed
for testing. For NCCL tests however, we need to make different workers using
different GPUs.

This change sets CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES on worker processes if share_gpu is False.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/phiberoptick/moby/commits/2842639e0e22bc2f91271603fb9990fa2ac8ad2e"},{"sha":"2fea30f14603613b40d8ce37c8ea7951f87abd1b","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"hack: add script to regenerate certificates

Certificates were originally added in c000cb64712349141596318dea2a8de2462c8f81,
but did not include a script to generate them. Current versions of Go expect
certificates to use SAN instead of Common Name fields, so updating the script
to include those;

    x509: certificate relies on legacy Common Name field, use SANs or temporarily
    enable Common Name matching with GODEBUG=x509ignoreCN=0

Some fields were updated to be a bit more descriptive (instead of "replaceme"),
and the `-text` option was used to include a human-readable variant of the
content.

Certificates were originally added in c000cb64712349141596318dea2a8de2462c8f81,
but did not include a script to generate them. Current versions of Go expect
certificates to use SAN instead of Common Name fields, so updating the script
to include those;

    x509: certificate relies on legacy Common Name field, use SANs or temporarily
    enable Common Name matching with GODEBUG=x509ignoreCN=0

Some fields were updated to be a bit more descriptive (instead of "replaceme"),
and the `-text` option was used to include a human-readable variant of the
content.

* Adding functions rbegin() and rend() functions to matrix class.
This is important to be more standard compliant with C++ and an ever increasing number of people using standard algorithms for better code readability- and maintainability.

The functions are copy pated from their counterparts (even though they should probably call the counterparts but this gave me some troube).
They return iterators using std::reverse_iterators

Follow up of an open feature request:
https://github.com/opencv/opencv/issues/4641

* Fix rbegin() and rend() and provide tests for them

* Removing unnecessary whitespaces

* Adding rbegin and rend to Mat_ class with the right parameters so we don't need to repeat the template argument.
An instantiating cv::Mat_<int> for example can call it's rbegin() function and doesn't need rbegin<int>() with this convience addition.

Follows what is done for forward iterators

* static cast the vector size (return size_t) to an int (that is required for opencv mat constructor)

Refactor error/warning count tracking to avoid pre-allocating an ID for Fibers that aren't yet mounted. Instead, we store a temporary reference to the Fiber itself and later check to see if it successfully mounted before merging pending error/warning counts.

This supports a custom-call case, where a logical operation can be lowered into
two HLOs (e.g., PerformX and PerformXDone). We can utilize this mechanism to
either hide host latencies between the pair of the custom-calls or the two calls
can more accurately identify the def-use relationship (typically PerformX is
scheduled right after all of its producers have been scheduled and PerformXDone

[{"sha":"7de009c346cd7c67b51fce3c87e855e4f5e3d1be","author":{"name":"Trent Lo","email":"7ddb1753734378bc8a5ee2f8f682002ac2d0087e@nvidia.com"},"message":"[XLA/GPU] Add CustomCallSchedule to give schedule hints to custom-calls.

Add schedule hints EARLY_AS_POSSIBLE and LATE_AS_POSSIBLE to custom-calls.
This supports a custom-call case, where a logical operation can be lowered into
two HLOs (e.g., PerformX and PerformXDone). We can utilize this mechanism to
either hide host latencies between the pair of the custom-calls or the two calls
can more accurately identify the def-use relationship (typically PerformX is
scheduled right after all of its producers have been scheduled and PerformXDone

Change-Id: Ic57e6298a70604e5f72b955daf7064fadfbfb3f0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/a27bbfd04c7cb03fc4f6b110e3032117bbaa375e"},{"sha":"9f594b848ac12c98518a544198fc1c0571f68ce1","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Support each worker using different GPUs in multi_process_runner

workers share the devices, which is desired to reduce the number of GPUs needed

different GPUs.

This change sets CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES on worker processes if share_gpu is False.

[{"sha":"115e471515813182b93066f5d0f445f25675f68b","author":{"name":"HattrickGenerator","email":"a7620a44cf7aa0cef4a7cd21c91e2fe85c5d1fe8@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #19967 from HattrickGenerator:master

* Adding functions rbegin() and rend() functions to matrix class.
This is important to be more standard compliant with C++ and an ever increasing number of people using standard algorithms for better code readability- and maintainability.

The functions are copy pated from their counterparts (even though they should probably call the counterparts but this gave me some troube).
They return iterators using std::reverse_iterators

Follow up of an open feature request:
https://github.com/opencv/opencv/issues/4641

* Fix rbegin() and rend() and provide tests for them

* Removing unnecessary whitespaces

* Adding rbegin and rend to Mat_ class with the right parameters so we don't need to repeat the template argument.
An instantiating cv::Mat_<int> for example can call it's rbegin() function and doesn't need rbegin<int>() with this convience addition.

Follows what is done for forward iterators

* static cast the vector size (return size_t) to an int (that is required for opencv mat constructor)

Co-authored-by: Stefan <stefan.gerl@tum.de>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/opencv/opencv/commits/115e471515813182b93066f5d0f445f25675f68b"}]

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

```

Initial attempt was to just skip the failing subtest (using the `test.disable_with_predicate` decorator), but that causes the following failure in non-ROCm builds

```
raise RuntimeError('You appear to be running a parameterized test case '
RuntimeError: You appear to be running a parameterized test case without having inherited from parameterized.TestCase. This is bad because none of your test cases are actually being run. You may also be using another decorator before the parameterized one, in which case you should reverse the order.
```

Reversing the decorator order results in a different error

```
ValueError: The test does not take parameters that were passed : {'use_adapt'} .
```

so abandoning that approach and adding a `no_rocm` tag to skip the test completely

The subtest being failing on the ROCm platform is `KPLTest.testTrainAndServe`

The error does not seem to be ROCm specific, and am hoping it will be root-caused and fixed in upstream.
Skipping these subtests for now to get the ROCm unit-tests passing again.

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

[{"sha":"bc3d20633950c6872119b6fcf64b02bfabdac8dc","author":{"name":"Abin Shahab","email":"aa5e48ffaae751ccd8830df151a27b555951f193@linkedin.com"},"message":"Resolves coredump caused by `tf.data.experimental.save` with prefetch

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/bc3d20633950c6872119b6fcf64b02bfabdac8dc"},{"sha":"8fbc6b24481fefb422e51e596a3211aa998262b4","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #49312 from ashahab/abin-load-segfault-r2.4

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Closes https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform/issues/22833","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605"},{"sha":"45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745"},{"sha":"47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remote provisioners require a connection config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e"},{"sha":"2b252ac677f1d99adcf08202c3047be2478a1055","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27910 from hashicorp/jbardin/remote-provisioners

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

Change-Id: Ic57e6298a70604e5f72b955daf7064fadfbfb3f0","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ashutosh1919/tensorflow/commits/a27bbfd04c7cb03fc4f6b110e3032117bbaa375e"},{"sha":"9f594b848ac12c98518a544198fc1c0571f68ce1","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Support each worker using different GPUs in multi_process_runner

workers share the devices, which is desired to reduce the number of GPUs needed
for testing. For NCCL tests however, we need to make different workers using
different GPUs.

This change sets CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES on worker processes if share_gpu is False.

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/angelcar/moby/commits/ef9ee10914a746f49fa2e4074bf92b4f025445a8"},{"sha":"80039b4699e36ceb0eb81109cd1686aaa805c5ec","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"systemd: set Limit* to infinity

There is a not-insignificant performance overhead for all containers (if
containerd is a child of Docker, which is the current setup) if systemd
sets rlimits on the main Docker daemon process (because the limits
propogate to all children).

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/angelcar/moby/commits/80039b4699e36ceb0eb81109cd1686aaa805c5ec"},{"sha":"7daf2db62a69cb6b341addf94d5da82759d7b6c2","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"systemd: don't limit tasks

Systemd sets a default of 512 tasks, which is far
too low to run many containers.

Note that TasksMax is only supported on systemd 226
and above.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/angelcar/moby/commits/7daf2db62a69cb6b341addf94d5da82759d7b6c2"},{"sha":"26eddc16a887e84f31ef540e0568cbb998dfe155","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"systemd: add "Delegate=yes" to docker's service file

We need to add delegate yes to docker's service file so that it can
manage the cgroups of the processes that it launches without systemd
interfering with them and moving the processes after it is reloaded.

       Delegate=
           Turns on delegation of further resource control partitioning to
           processes of the unit. For unprivileged services (i.e. those
           using the User= setting), this allows processes to create a
           subhierarchy beneath its control group path. For privileged
           services and scopes, this ensures the processes will have all
           control group controllers enabled.

This is the proper fix for issue moby/moby#20152

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/angelcar/moby/commits/26eddc16a887e84f31ef540e0568cbb998dfe155"},{"sha":"f30757f439bce71dec312d0797e9c80a06e98058","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"systemd: set systemd KillMode

Certificates were originally added in c000cb64712349141596318dea2a8de2462c8f81,
but did not include a script to generate them. Current versions of Go expect
certificates to use SAN instead of Common Name fields, so updating the script
to include those;

    x509: certificate relies on legacy Common Name field, use SANs or temporarily
    enable Common Name matching with GODEBUG=x509ignoreCN=0

Some fields were updated to be a bit more descriptive (instead of "replaceme"),
and the `-text` option was used to include a human-readable variant of the
content.

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform
